Sarah Shapiro

* On the new G-III
& Saks alliance: There has been some confusion in the industry regarding G-=
III Apparel=E2=80=99s decision to invest in the recent Saks=E2=80=93Neiman =
Marcus combination alongside Salesforce, Amazon, and Authentic Brands Group=
=2E But never underestimate a brand-=
management company=E2=80=99s confidence i=
n their ability to monetize a downslope. G-III, which owns brands like DKNY=
 and Karl Lagerfeld, and has a licensing agreement with fellow mall-brand r=
oll-up PVH, is almost certainly going to benefit from advantaged
store placement and access to valuable=E2=80=94and otherwise expensive=E2=
=80=94consumer insights and shopping behavior. There are a lot more places =
where we could see G-III apparel on Saks=E2=80=99 racks=E2=80=94not least a=
t the Saks Off 5th and Neiman Marcus Last Call discount chains, which are a=
 significant part of the business and always in need of inventory. Most G-I=
II brands aren=E2=80=99t high-end enough for Saks or Neiman to convincingly=
 sell to consumers of luxury goods.)

Meanwhile, it=E2=80=99s easy to mistake the
Saks-Neiman deal, and the profusion of distressed-asset companies (like the=
 newly created Catalyst), as inauspicious omens for the industry. But the t=
ruth is that the existence of these various holding companies=E2=80=94inclu=
ding ABG, PVH, and G-III=E2=80=94indicates a general optimism that post-pri=
me brands and stores can be operated effectively beyond their peaks. It may=
 seem depressing on some level, but it=E2=80=99s also opportunistic.

