Dupes=E2=80=94cheaper versions of expensive items that mostly look and
feel the same=E2=80=94will always be a feature of the fashion industry. To =
be clear, these are not the illicit knockoffs of Prada and YSL handbags tha=
t made Canal Street famous=E2=80=93=E2=80=93we=E2=80=99re talking legitimat=
e imitation merchandise sold at Amazon Marketplace, Target, and even on the=
 higher rungs of the fashion business.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

But dupes are especially ubiquitous in makeup, skincare, and fragrance, whe=
re the
public is often seeking a more affordable alternative to whatever highlight=
er or perfume is trending at the moment. People, in other words, are asking=
 for dupes, and brands are able to serve them up because of an increasingly=
 de minimis barrier to entry when it comes to making beauty products and th=
e quickening pace of product development. Social media has even turned the =
pursuit of a really good imitation product into a sort of competition, with=
 virality and clout
bestowed upon the discoverer. In fact, the sentiment toward dupes in beauty=
 has largely bent positive since brands like e.l.f. Cosmetics, among others=
, are disrupting an industry in which most people can=E2=80=99t afford many=
 of the most viral products.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

On Monday, two trade outlets took competing stands on the issue: Beauty Ind=
ependent ran a positive piece about Target=E2=80=99s embrace of MCoBeauty, =
an
Australian brand that will soon be selling a $15 knockoff of Charlotte Tilb=
ury=E2=80=99s nearly $50 Hollywood Flawless Filter =E2=80=9Cdown to the rid=
ged gold cap.=E2=80=9D (Among MCoBeauty=E2=80=99s other bestsellers are dup=
es of Dior lip oil and Drunk Elephant=E2=80=99s bronzing drops.) Meridith R=
ojas, MCoBeauty=E2=80=99s C.M.O., told Beauty Independent that she believes=
 =E2=80=9Caccessibility is a form of innovation,=E2=80=9D and that =E2=80=
=9Cthe internet is making it so that we can innovate quickly. We can see wh=
at=E2=80=99s trending, we can
see what people want, and we can give it to them at a price that they can a=
fford. We=E2=80=99re democratizing luxury.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Over at The Business of Fashion, one of my favorite beauty writers, my pal =
Brennan Kilbane, wrote about the success of Charlotte Tilbury, which was ac=
quired by Puig at a $1.2 billion valuation in 2020. The piece was pegged to=
 the brand=E2=80=99s new dupe-fighting campaign,
=E2=80=9CLegendary. For a Reason,=E2=80=9D in which Tilbury, herself, decri=
es the copycats that make cheaper versions of her expensive products. She a=
ppears to be very distraught over the matter, and even goes so far as to sa=
y that the lower quality of the imitation version is a disservice to the cu=
stomer: =E2=80=9CWhen you dupe, you dupe the consumer.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

Democratizing Beauty
--------------------

Of course, both sides have a point. Imitation may be a form of
flattery, but it=E2=80=99s also the raison d=E2=80=99=C3=AAtre for copyrigh=
t law, the patent system, and the intellectual property bar. And, obviously=
, there is nothing a founder hates more than seeing others copy their produ=
cts, branding, or ideas. And Tilbury is genuinely pissed. =E2=80=9CShe=E2=
=80=99s getting down in the mud with this campaign,=E2=80=9D said a person =
with knowledge of the matter who was surprised that the founder was =E2=80=
=9Cso openly bothered by the under-$15 dupes.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

=C2=A0

And yet, chances are that the person buying MCoBeauty=E2=80=99s $15 primer =
was never going to buy Tilbury=E2=80=99s version. While some of the Instagr=
am comments below the BoF piece support the founder, many voice a widely he=
ld belief that the proliferation of dupes is indeed growing the market, not=
 cannibalizing it. In other words, there=E2=80=99s a reason why Dior isn=E2=
=80=99t worried about Target=E2=80=99s bestselling e.l.f. $8 lip oils, nor =
is Herm=C3=A8s
losing sleep over the $80 =E2=80=9CWalmart Birkin.=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

In fact, a founder=E2=80=99s concern over a dupe is usually a tell that a l=
arger problem is afoot. To wit: I heard that Charlotte Tilbury descended fr=
om Sephora=E2=80=99s domestic number one brand in 2023 to its number two la=
st year, falling behind Sol de Janeiro. A person close to Sephora told me t=
hat Charlotte Tilbury also saw year-over-year declines, with December
being =E2=80=9Cparticularly bad.=E2=80=9D According to this person, the col=
lection of six =E2=80=9Cneuroscents=E2=80=9D that launched last May didn=E2=
=80=99t meet expectations, either. (Spokespeople for Charlotte Tilbury and =
Sephora declined to comment.)

=C2=A0

Of course, Charlotte Tilbury is still hugely successful. I received an e-ma=
il from a brand spokesperson this week with a mountain of boastful stats, i=
ncluding that Charlotte Tilbury remains the number
one prestige face brand, the number one premium makeup brand, and the numbe=
r one highlighter and face powder brand in the U.S., per Circana. And it wa=
s probably inevitable that sales of Charlotte Tilbury would drop at Sephora=
 once the brand entered some 600 Ulta Beauty stores almost a year ago. As t=
he person close to Sephora explained, it=E2=80=99s normal for a brand=E2=80=
=99s business to drop 20 to 40 percent at the retailer once it decides to e=
xpand its distribution.

Doth She Protest Too
Much?
--------------------

Anyway, you can=E2=80=99t help but wonder why Tilbury is mounting this
fight now, rather than devoting resources to creating the next Hollywood Fl=
awless Filter, Hollywood Contour Wand, or Pillow Talk. Tilbury was a catego=
ry disruptor, and she hasn=E2=80=99t had a new hero product in years. When =
you go the luxury beauty route=E2=80=93=E2=80=93especially when first-to-ma=
rket innovations and hero or viral products are involved=E2=80=93=E2=80=93d=
upes are now simply a cost of doing business.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Unfortunately, the downside to being first to market is that everyone catch=
es up and tries to do the same. And the only counterattack is to respond fa=
ster, find ways to support your hero products, and do it again and again. =
=E2=80=9C[Charlotte] has chosen to go about it in a way that seems juvenile=
,=E2=80=9D said a beauty marketer who has worked with some of the biggest m=
akeup brands in the world. =E2=80=9CYou can still be =E2=80=98the original=
=E2=80=99 without having to
make a grandstand about dupes.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Yes, it=E2=80=99s true that launching new products is always a risk=E2=80=
=94especially when mainstays like Hollywood Flawless Filter, Airbrush Flawl=
ess Finish Setting Powder, and the contour wands account for so much of Til=
bury=E2=80=99s business. But there are better ways to shift the focus back =
to the brand=E2=80=99s heroes without attacking dupe culture, like adding i=
ngredients to make the products do new tricks,
or even deploying marketing spend to make new claims about old ingredients.=
 Alas, these could be more expensive undertakings, but surely, it would be =
a better use of capital than a reactionary and defensive P.R. campaign. As =
always, what people choose to spend on skincare and makeup is at their disc=
retion, but I=E2=80=99d argue that by now, we all know how much it actually=
 costs to make beauty products. Perhaps some of the brands charging $50 or =
$100 for something that costs
$5 to make are the ones really duping the consumer.=C2=A0=C2=A0

