px;line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Dupes=E2=80=94cheaper versions of expensiv=
e items that mostly look and
feel the same=E2=80=94will always be a feature of the fashion industry. To =
be clear, these are not the illicit knockoffs of Prada and YSL handbags tha=
t made Canal Street famous=E2=80=93=E2=80=93we=E2=80=99re talking legitimat=
e imitation merchandise sold at Amazon Marketplace, Target, and even on the=
 higher rungs of the fashion business.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin=
-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">But dupes =
are <em>especially</em> ubiquitous in makeup, skincare, and fragrance, wher=
e the
public is often seeking a more affordable alternative to whatever highlight=
er or perfume is trending at the moment. People, in other words, are <em>as=
king</em> for dupes, and brands are able to serve them up because of an inc=
reasingly <em>de minimis </em>barrier to entry when it comes to making beau=
ty products and the quickening pace of product development. Social media ha=
s even turned the pursuit of a really good imitation product into a sort of=
 competition, with virality and clout
bestowed upon the discoverer. In fact, the sentiment toward dupes in beauty=
 has largely bent positive since brands like e.l.f. Cosmetics, among others=
, are disrupting an industry in which most people can=E2=80=99t afford many=
 of the most viral products.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">On Monday, two trade=
 outlets took competing stands on the issue: <em>Beauty Independent</em> ra=
n a positive piece about Target=E2=80=99s embrace of MCoBeauty, an
Australian brand that will soon be selling a $15 knockoff of Charlotte Tilb=
ury=E2=80=99s nearly $50 Hollywood Flawless Filter =E2=80=9Cdown to the rid=
ged gold cap.=E2=80=9D (Among MCoBeauty=E2=80=99s other bestsellers are dup=
es of Dior lip oil and Drunk Elephant=E2=80=99s bronzing drops.) <strong>Me=
ridith Rojas</strong>, MCoBeauty=E2=80=99s C.M.O., told <em>Beauty Independ=
ent</em> that she believes =E2=80=9Caccessibility is a form of innovation,=
=E2=80=9D and that =E2=80=9Cthe internet is making it so that we can innova=
te quickly. We can see what=E2=80=99s trending, we can
see what people want, and we can give it to them at a price that they can a=
fford. We=E2=80=99re democratizing luxury.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Over at The Bus=
iness of Fashion<em>, </em>one of my favorite beauty writers, my pal <stron=
g>Brennan</strong> <strong>Kilbane</strong>, wrote about the success of Cha=
rlotte Tilbury, which was acquired by Puig at a $1.2 billion valuation in 2=
020. The piece was pegged to the brand=E2=80=99s new dupe-fighting campaign=
,
=E2=80=9CLegendary. For a Reason,=E2=80=9D in which <strong>Tilbury</strong=
>, herself, decries the copycats that make cheaper versions of her expensiv=
e products. She appears to be <em>very</em> distraught over the matter, and=
 even goes so far as to say that the lower quality of the imitation version=
 is a disservice to the customer: =E2=80=9CWhen you dupe, you dupe the cons=
umer.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p></div>
