bottom:32px;"><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;In=
ter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;=
line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Of course, both sides have a point. Imitation m=
ay be a form of
flattery, but it=E2=80=99s also the <em>raison d=E2=80=99=C3=AAtre </em>for=
 copyright law, the patent system, and the intellectual property bar. And, =
<em>obviously</em>, there is nothing a founder hates more than seeing other=
s copy their products, branding, or ideas. And Tilbury is genuinely pissed.=
 =E2=80=9CShe=E2=80=99s getting down in the mud with this campaign,=E2=80=
=9D said a person with knowledge of the matter who was surprised that the f=
ounder was =E2=80=9Cso openly bothered by the under-$15 dupes.=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;
margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">And =
yet, chances are that the person buying MCoBeauty=E2=80=99s $15 primer was =
<em>never</em> going to buy Tilbury=E2=80=99s version. While some of the In=
stagram comments below the BoF piece support the founder, many voice a wide=
ly held belief that the proliferation of dupes is indeed growing the market=
, not cannibalizing it. In other words, there=E2=80=99s a reason why Dior i=
sn=E2=80=99t worried about Target=E2=80=99s bestselling e.l.f. $8 lip oils,=
 nor is Herm=C3=A8s
losing sleep over the $80 =E2=80=9CWalmart Birkin.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"=
margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0=
px;">In fact, a founder=E2=80=99s concern over a dupe is usually a tell tha=
t a larger problem is afoot. To wit: I heard that Charlotte Tilbury descend=
ed from Sephora=E2=80=99s domestic number one brand in 2023 to its <em>numb=
er two </em>last year, falling behind Sol de Janeiro. A person close to Sep=
hora told me that Charlotte Tilbury also saw year-over-year declines, with =
December
being =E2=80=9Cparticularly bad.=E2=80=9D According to this person, the col=
lection of six =E2=80=9Cneuroscents=E2=80=9D that launched last May didn=E2=
=80=99t meet expectations, either. (Spokespeople for Charlotte Tilbury and =
Sephora declined to comment.)</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Of course, Charlotte Tilbury is still huge=
ly successful. I received an e-mail from a brand spokesperson this week wit=
h a mountain of boastful stats, including that Charlotte Tilbury remains th=
e <em>number
one</em> prestige face brand, the <em>number one</em> premium makeup brand,=
 and the <em>number one</em> highlighter and face powder brand in the U.S.,=
 per Circana. And it was probably inevitable that sales of Charlotte Tilbur=
y would drop at Sephora once the brand entered some 600 Ulta Beauty stores =
almost a year ago. As the person close to Sephora explained, it=E2=80=99s n=
ormal for a brand=E2=80=99s business to drop 20 to 40 percent at the retail=
er once it decides to expand its distribution.</p></div>
