line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Anyway, you can=E2=80=99t help but wonder why T=
ilbury is mounting this
fight now, rather than devoting resources to creating the <em>next </em>Hol=
lywood Flawless Filter, Hollywood Contour Wand, or Pillow Talk. Tilbury was=
 a category disruptor, and she hasn=E2=80=99t had a new hero product in <em=
>years</em>. When you go the luxury beauty route=E2=80=93=E2=80=93especiall=
y when first-to-market innovations <em>and </em>hero or viral products are =
involved=E2=80=93=E2=80=93dupes are now simply a cost of doing business.=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margi=
n:0;
margin-bottom:0px;">Unfortunately, the downside to being first to market is=
 that everyone catches up and tries to do the same. And the only counteratt=
ack is to respond faster, find ways to support your hero products, and do i=
t again and again. =E2=80=9C[Charlotte] has chosen to go about it in a way =
that seems juvenile,=E2=80=9D said a beauty marketer who has worked with so=
me of the biggest makeup brands in the world. =E2=80=9CYou can still be =E2=
=80=98the original=E2=80=99 without having to
make a grandstand about dupes.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margi=
n-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Yes, it=E2=80=99s true that=
 launching new products is always a risk=E2=80=94especially when mainstays =
like Hollywood Flawless Filter, Airbrush Flawless Finish Setting Powder, an=
d the contour wands account for so much of Tilbury=E2=80=99s business. But =
there are better ways to shift the focus back to the brand=E2=80=99s heroes=
 without attacking dupe culture, like adding ingredients to make the produc=
ts do new tricks,
or even deploying marketing spend to make <em>new</em> claims about <em>old=
</em> ingredients. Alas, these could be more expensive undertakings, but su=
rely, it would be a better use of capital than a reactionary and defensive =
P.R. campaign. As always, what people choose to spend on skincare and makeu=
p is at their discretion, but I=E2=80=99d argue that by now, we all know ho=
w much it <em>actually</em> costs to make beauty products. Perhaps some of =
the brands charging $50 or $100 for something that costs
$5 to make are the ones <em>really</em> duping the consumer.=C2=A0=C2=A0</p=
></div>
